{{More citations needed|date=August 2015}} {{Infobox person | name = David Scott Blackhall | image = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | alt = | caption = | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name --> | birth_date = {{Birth date|1910|05|10}} | birth_place = [[Cirencester]], [[Gloucestershire]], United Kingdom | death_date = {{Death date and age|1981|09|14|1910|05|10}} | death_place = | nationality = British | other_names = | occupation = Radio host | years_active = 1960s-1980s | known_for = ''In Touch'' | notable_works = }}
'''David Scott Blackhall''' was a [[radio]] personality, author and [[poet]].
==Life and career== He was born in [[Cirencester]], [[Gloucestershire]] on 9 May 1910 to George William and Annie Blackhall.<ref>{{cite book|date=1969|url=https://books.google.com/?id=kHREAAAAMAAJ&q=David+Scott+Blackhall+radio&dq=David+Scott+Blackhall+radio|title=Contemporary Authors: First revision, Volumes 5-8|publisher=[[Gale (publisher)|Gale Research]]|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> After an accident in his teens, in which he sustained a detached retina, he lost the sight in his left eye. He underwent an operation in about 1943 to restore some sight in this eye, but the operation was unsuccessful. The eyesight in his right eye began to seriously deteriorate in the 50s and an operation for cataracts was unsuccessful, leaving him totally blind by age 45.
In 1961 his autobiography ''This House Had Windows'' was published and in which he explained he learned braille, which took him three weeks to learn the system.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=KX8iAAAAMAAJ&q=David+Scott+Blackhall+radio&dq=David+Scott+Blackhall+radio&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAGoVChMIi8jUwa3CxwIVlxaSCh3DgQbB This house had windows], page 102, 1962, I. Oblonsky</ref> The 'David Scott Blackhall Award for Services to the Blind' was named in his honour by the [[BBC]] radio's ''[[In Touch (radio series)|In Touch]]'' programme, a programme which Blackhall first hosted.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=1bJIAAAAYAAJ&q=David+Scott+Blackhall+radio&dq=David+Scott+Blackhall+radio&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCIQ6AEwAWoVChMIi8jUwa3CxwIVlxaSCh3DgQbB he New Beacon, Volume 76, Issues 894-904], 1992, page 475, [[RNIB]]</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Street |first=Sean |date=2015 |title=Historical Dictionary of British Radio |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Df-dCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA180&dq=David+Scott+Blackhall+radio#v=onepage&q=David%20Scott%20Blackhall%20radio&f=false |publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield]] |page=180 |isbn=1442249234 |accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> Another award started in Blackhall's memory was the Patients' Aid Association's David Scott Blackhall Memorial Award which would award a cash prize to individuals making a positive impact to the blind community.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=y25MAAAAYAAJ&q=David+Scott+Blackhall+radio&dq=David+Scott+Blackhall+radio&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAzgKahUKEwjwpKO-t8LHAhVTGpIKHT3TANI Country Life], Volume 180, 1986, page 1428</ref> Another blind colleague of Blackhall's at Radio 4 was Jill Allen-King.<ref> {{cite book |last=Allen-King |first=Jill |date=2011 |title=Just Jill:The Autobiography of Jill Allen-King |url=https://books.google.com/?id=bhm5BAAAQBAJ&pg=PT53&dq=David+Scott+Blackhall+radio#v=onepage&q=David%20Scott%20Blackhall%20radio&f=|publisher=[[Paul Andrews (producer)|Andrews UK Limited]] |page= |isbn=1907792058 |accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> Blackhall was also a member of [[Rotary International]] since 1935 and, in 1942, founded the Rotary Club of [[Elstree]] & [[Borehamwood]].<ref>{{cite journal |last= |first= |last2= |first2= |date=February 1970 |title=How We Climbed The Ben |url=https://books.google.com/?id=PTUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA20&dq=David+Scott+Blackhall+radio |publisher=''[[The Rotarian]]'' |volume=116 |issue=2 |pages= 20 |access-date=22 August 2015}}</ref>
In 1969 during one of his radio editions of "In Touch", he commented on a group of blind people who had climbed Mt Kilimanjaro, the highest mountain in Africa, and went on to say that Britain's highest mountain was Ben Nevis - if anyone was interested. It seemed they were, as he had a flood of letters from interested listeners who wished to make that climb. With the help of local people in the town of Fort William, a weekend was arranged at the Milton Hotel - appropriately Milton was a blind poet - and a group of 15 visually impaired men and women with local sighted companions and Blackhall at the helm, made the climb, arriving at the summit to the sound of the bagpipes, played by one of the group. It was a proud moment for him and the start of the Milton Mountaineers, who went on to meet annually to climb more of Britain's and Ireland's highest peaks. One of Blackhall's poems, "Prayer", is still recited by the leader of the Mountaineers at each summit. Other works of Blackhall's were ''Dark Is A Long Way'', a radio play about his Blind experiences that was broadcast in Britain in September 1958. Blackhall hosted ''In Touch''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-15184993|title=In Touch marks 50th anniversary|date=October 7, 2011|publisher=bbc.com|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> until a week before his death,<ref>{{cite book |last=Donovan|first=Paul|date=1991|url=https://books.google.com/?id=79IaAQAAIAAJ&q=David+Scott+Blackhall+radio&dq=David+Scott+Blackhall+radio|title=The radio companion|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|isbn=0246136480|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> on September 14, 1981, aged 71.<ref name="Undaunted ">{{cite book |last=Olstrom |first=Clifford E. |date=2012 |title=Undaunted by Blindness, 2nd Edition |url=https://books.google.com/?id=k9K77s1IRgoC&pg=PT48&dq=David+Scott+Blackhall+radio#v=onepage&q=David%20Scott%20Blackhall%20radio&f=false |publisher=eBookIt.com |page= |isbn=0982272197 |accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> He had three daughters: Anne (b. 1936), (Leader of the Milton Mountaineers from 1992 to 2005); Jane (b. 1940) and Susan (b. 1949) and was married to Edna (née Westwood).
